Yes, absolutely — VBA macros are a great fit here since you already know Excel. Here's how this approach compares and how to make it work:

How it would work with VBA

New Excel file arrives in the shared folder
A "master" Excel workbook runs a VBA macro that opens the new file, pulls the data, refreshes all your dashboard charts/pivots, and saves the output
The dashboard workbook is always up to date — team opens it directly from the shared drive
Two ways to trigger the macro automatically

Option A — Windows Task Scheduler (simplest) Schedule the master workbook to open at set intervals (e.g. every 15 min or hourly). The Workbook_Open event fires the macro automatically. No Python needed at all.

Option B — VBA file watcher loop A VBA timer loop inside the master workbook checks if a new/modified file exists in the folder using Dir() and FileDateTime(). When it detects a change, it triggers the dashboard refresh macro immediately.

